top.value: The high level objective of the PMU is to achieve cost-effective, efficient and timely delivery of the research and uptake, capacity building and knowledge management programmes for HVT. The contract split into two parts; Part 1, lasting 15 months, will involve procurement of a review of the literature and evidence available under the four identified research areas and will deliver a series of state of knowledge papers, that will be used to identify and prioritise what future primary research might be undertaken in Part 2 and its scope. A detailed research plan will be proposed for Part 2 based on outcomes from Part 1. Part 2 is expected to run for 4 years.

The participating organisations agreed to produce a joint Flagship Report that will provide a conceptual framework to think about the economic corridors and to enable a holistic appraisal of large corridor projects. The framework will extend beyond developing transport corridors and focus on the ultimate goals of having positive impacts on national and local economic activity, jobs, inequality, gender empowerment, and poverty.

BRACE II (Building Resilience through Asset Creation and Enhancement) is a DFID-funded programme that aims to improve food security and resilience, primarily through reducing vulnerability to climate variability and extremes. It also aims to reduce vulnerability to communal conflict by increasing social solidarity and cohesion. BRACE II is a 5 year programme and will be implemented in 2 phases. DFID is investing £20 million in the first phase. BRACE II is being implemented in five states in Greater Upper Nile in Sudan (Northern Bar el Ghazal, Western Bar el Ghazal, Warrap, Lakes and Eastern Equatorial states). The BRACE M&E team will seek to support all BRACE II partners on M&E in order to produce robust evidence and learning, to establish a feedback mechanism that gives communities a voice and enables two way communication and accountability to beneficiaries, and to communicate with each other effectively in order to share experiences and knowledge and improve delivery. We will also seek to conduct independent M&E activities to answer a set of key questions at intervention level (are we doing the things right?) and programme level (are they the right things to do?).

DFID is providing £16 million to undertake a five year research programme (Sustainable Energy, Access and Gender - SEAG) to deliver evidence that will shape the global effort to provide universal access to sustainable modern energy services by 2030. IMC was contracted to conduct the independent review, which is required to provide robust evidence on key features of the SEAG programme taken as a whole.
